===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|castle|lang=enm}}, {{term|castel|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|castel|lang=ang}}, {{term|castell|lang=ang}}, {{term|cæstel|lang=ang}}, {{term|ceastel|ċeastel|a town, village, castle|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|kastel|a camp|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|castellum||small camp, fort|lang=la}}, diminutive of {{etyl|la}} {{term|castrum||camp, fort, citadel, stronghold|lang=la}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|kat-|hut, shed|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|castel|lang=sco}}, {{term|castell||castle|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|kastiel||castle|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|kasteel||castle|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Kastell||castle|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|kastel||citadel|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|kastell||citadel|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|kastali||castle|lang=is}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|casa||cottage, hut|lang=la}}. The Middle English word was reinforced by {{etyl|ONF.|-}} {{term|castel|lang=fro}}, from the same Latin root. Related also to {{etyl|got|-}} {{term|||tr=hēþjō|chamber|lang=got}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|heaþor||restraint, confinement, enclosure, prison|lang=ang}}. See also {{l|en|casino}}, {{l|en|cassock}}.

